text: : , ; ) ( 0 9 8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 : , ; ) ( 0 9 8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 The Journal of Antibiotics (2021) 74:593–595 https://doi.org/10.1038/s41429-021-00442-1 6,9-Dihydroxytetrangulol, a novel angucyclinone antibiotic accumulated in kiqO gene disruptant in the biosynthesis of kinanthraquinone Katsuyuki Sakai Shunji Takahashi Received: 23 March 2021 / Revised: 1 June 2021 / Accepted: 18 June 2021 / Published online: 7 July 2021 © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to the Japan Antibiotics Research Association 2021 Abstract A novel angucyclinone, 6,9-dihydroxytetrangulol, was isolated from Streptomyces lividans TK23 transformed with a kinanthraquinone biosynthetic gene cluster in which the kiqO gene was disrupted. The chemical structure was elucidated by spectroscopic analyses. It showed signiﬁcant antibacterial activities with an IC50 value of 1.9 μM against Staphylococcus aureus and moderate anticancer activities against HL-60 cells. The angucycline group of antibiotics has a characteristic tetracyclic benz[a]anthracene structure and exhibits various biological activities, such as antibacterial and antitumor activities [1, 2]. Angucyclines/angucyclinones are produced by type II polyketide synthase (PKS), and their chemical diversity is due to tailoring enzymes, such as oxygenase, methyltransferase, and glycosyltransferase [3]. We recently identiﬁed a kinanthraquinone biosynthetic gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. SN-593 [4–6]. The kiq cluster consists of type II PKS and tailoring enzymes, which have the potential to expand the chemical structure. In this to generate novel biosynthetic intermediates that study,

As a result, we found a biosynthetic intermediate accumulated in the kiqO gene disruptant that was heterologously expressed in S. lividans TK23 (Supplementary text, Tables S1 and S2).

The disruptant was cultured in K1 ﬂasks containing the SK2 medium (1.4% soluble starch, 0.35% glucose, 0.35% yeast extract, 0.21% bacto peptone, 0.21% beef extract, 0.014% KH2PO4, and 0.042% MgSO4; pH 7.6) at 28 °C for the seed culture was 3 days. For production cultures, inoculated into each K1 ﬂask containing 70 ml of tryptic soy broth medium (total 17 L) and incubated at 28 °C for 3 days. Equal amounts of acetone were added to the pro- duction culture. The acetone extract was ﬁltered to remove bacterial cells and evaporated under reduced pressure to remove acetone. The remaining aqueous solution (24 L) was extracted twice with an equal volume of EtOAc (24 L × 2). The organic layer was dried to obtain the crude extract (4.1 g). The EtOAc extract was fractionated by Sephadex LH20 column chromatography (40 i.d. × 215 mm) and eluted with MeOH to obtain 14 fractions. The target fraction was detected by UPLC analysis, concentrated in vacuo, and puriﬁed by HPLC equipped with a PEGASIL ODS column (20 i.d. × 250 mm) with an isocratic solvent system of 60% acetonitrile-water and 0.02% formic acid solution at a ﬂow rate of 10 ml min−1 to obtain a new compound (1, 6.3 mg) (Fig. 1a) as a blue amorphous [UV (MeOH) λmax nm (log ε): 236 (4.11), 266 (sh, 3.95), 327 (3.90), and 459 (3.43) (Fig. S1), IR (ATR) νmax: 3194,

The molecular formula of compound 1 was determined to be C19H12O6 (found m/z 337.0702 [M + H]+, calculated m/z 337.0707 [M + H]+) by HRESIMS and required 14 degrees of unsaturation (Fig. S3). The IR spectrum indicated char- acteristic absorption at 3194, 1603, and 1576 cm−1, sug- gesting the presence of hydroxyl and carbonyl groups. We speculated that compound 1 had a benzo[a]anthracene-7,12- dione skeleton. The chemical structure of 1 was determined by 1D and 2D NMR analyses (Figs. S4–S9). All direct connections for protons and carbons in 1 were determined by the HSQC experiment. The 1H and 13C data of 1 are shown in Table 1. The NMR data measured in DMSO-d6 indicated the pre- sence of one methyl, ﬁve sp2 methine, eleven sp2 non- protonated aromatic carbons, and two carbonyl carbons. Subsequently, HMBC correlations from H-5 (δH 7.54) to C-6 (δC 155.4), C-6a (δC 119.7), and C-12b suggested the presence of another six-membered ring (Fig. 1b, c). The ROESY correlation between H-4 and H-5 and HMBC correlations from H-4 to C-5 (δC 118.8) and from H-5 to C-4 suggested that H-4 and H-5 were located in the peri positions and the two six-membered rings were fused. Therefore, the positions of all hydroxyl groups were determined using the above-mentioned HMBC correlations. These data showed that 1 was a new compound, and its structure was similar to that of dehydrorabelomycin [8] and 6-hydroxytetrangulol [9]. Here, we named the new 6-hydroxytetragulol derivative 6,9-dihydroxytetrangulol (6,9-DHT) (Fig. 1a).

The activities of 1 were evaluated against Staphylo- coccus aureus, Escherichia coli, Candida albicans, and Plasmodium falciparum. Compound 1 showed growth inhibition against the tested strains, except for E. coli. and showed strong growth inhibition against S. aureus and C. albicans at 1.9 and 1.1 μM, respectively (Table S4). The IC50 value of 1 against S. aureus was lower than that of chloramphenicol, suggesting that 1 might be a good can- didate antimicrobial agent. To date, rabelomycin derivatives have been reported to demonstrate antimicrobial activity against gram-positive bacteria [1, 10] but not against C. albicans [11–13]. Integrating our data with previous reports, we speculated that the catechol moiety in the D-ring of 6,9-DHT might have a signiﬁcant role in its antifungal activity. To evaluate whether 6,9-DHT could be a potential antimicrobial candidate against S. aureus, we also tested the cytotoxic activity of compound 1 against tumour cells. However, 1 showed modest cytotoxicity against HL-60 and HeLa cells with IC50 values of 5.1 and 12.5 μM, respec- tively (Table S5). Finally, our results indicated that 1 had the potential to be used as an anti-Candida agent.
